bay_county_names <-
  c(
    "Alameda",
    "Contra Costa",
    "Marin",
    "Napa",
    "San Francisco",
    "San Mateo",
    "Santa Clara",
    "Solano",
    "Sonoma"
  )

bay_blockgroups <-
  bay_county_names %>%
  map(function(x){
    block_groups("CA",x,progress_bar=F) %>%
      pull(GEOID)
  }) %>% unlist()

bay_counties <-
  counties("CA", cb = F, progress_bar=F) %>% 
  filter(NAME %in% bay_county_names)

scc_blockgroups <-
  block_groups("CA","Santa Clara", cb=F, progress_bar=F)

sj_boundary <-
  places("CA", cb=F, progress_bar=F) %>% 
  filter(NAME == "San Jose")

sj_blockgroups <-
  scc_blockgroups %>% 
  dplyr::select(GEOID) %>%
  st_join(sj_boundary %>% dplyr::select(geometry), left = F) %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  left_join(scc_blockgroups %>% dplyr::select(GEOID)) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

sj_blockgroups <-
  sj_blockgroups %>%

V1: Macro method (Bay Area normalization)

bay_pop <-
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "county:*", 
    regionin = "state:06",
    vars = "B01003_001E"
  ) %>% 
  mutate(fips = paste0(state,county)) %>% 
  filter(fips %in% bay_counties$GEOID) %>% 
  pull(B01003_001E) %>% 
  sum()

bay_sg_pop <-
  ca_home_200329 %>% 
  filter(census_block_group %in% bay_blockgroups) %>% 
  pull(number_devices_residing) %>% 
  sum()

bay_multiplier <- bay_pop/bay_sg_pop
  
sj_weekly_200329_v1 <-
  sj_weekly_200329 %>% 
  mutate(visit_counts = raw_visit_counts*bay_multiplier)

sj_weekly_200329_v1_sum <- 
  sj_weekly_200329_v1 %>% 
  pull(visit_counts) %>% 
  sum()

sj_weekly_200329_v1_sum
## [1] 6743150

Pro: super easy Con: requires a somewhat arbitrary decision on the scale at which the multiplier is created.

V2: Micro method for recorded + Bay Area normalization for unrecorded

First, a function that breaks out the visitor_home_cbgs column.

sum(sj_weekly_200329$visitor_home_cbgs == "{}")/nrow(sj_weekly_200329)
## [1] 0.9303839
# almost all places have no visitor CBG information (i.e. < 5 visitors from that CBG) at all! i don't recall it being THAT sparse... but this is probably because weekly patterns are more granular than monthly patterns, and because of reduced visits right now.

expand_origins <- function(patterns_data){
  
  temp <- NULL
  
  for(row in 1:nrow(patterns_data)){
    
    # print(row)
    
    if(patterns_data$visitor_home_cbgs[row] == "{}"){
      
      data <- 
        data.frame(
          safegraph_place_id = patterns_data$safegraph_place_id[row],
          origin_census_block_group = NA,
          origin_visitor_counts = patterns_data$raw_visitor_counts[row]
        )
      
    } else {
      
      json <- 
        patterns_data$visitor_home_cbgs[row] %>% 
        fromJSON() %>% 
        unlist() %>% 
        as.data.frame() %>% 
        rownames_to_column() %>% 
        rename(
          origin_census_block_group = "rowname",
          origin_visitor_counts = "."
        )
      
      unrecorded <- 
        patterns_data$raw_visitor_counts[row] -  
        sum(json$origin_visitor_counts)
      
      data <- 
        json %>% 
        rbind(
          data.frame(
            origin_census_block_group = NA,
            origin_visitor_counts = unrecorded
          )
        ) %>% 
        mutate(
          safegraph_place_id = patterns_data$safegraph_place_id[row]
        )
      
    }
    
    temp <-
      temp %>% 
      rbind(data)
  }
  
  temp <-
    temp %>% left_join(patterns_data)
  
  return(temp)
}

Now we join this expanded column back to the original patterns data and also add home panel device counts and census populations to each origin block group

ca_counties_fips <-
  counties("CA", cb = F, progress_bar=F) %>%
  pull(COUNTYFP)

ca_pop_blockgroup <-
  ca_counties_fips %>% 
  map_dfr(function(x){
    getCensus(
      name = "acs/acs5",
      vintage = 2018,
      region = "block group:*", 
      regionin = paste0("state:06+county:",x),
      vars = "B01003_001E"
    )
  }) %>% 
  transmute(
    origin_census_block_group = paste0(
      state,county,tract,block_group
    ),
    pop = B01003_001E
  )

sj_weekly_200329_expand <-
  sj_weekly_200329 %>%
  expand_origins() %>% 
  left_join(
    ca_home_200329 %>%
      dplyr::select(
        origin_census_block_group = census_block_group,
        number_devices_residing
      )
  ) %>% 
  left_join(
    ca_pop_blockgroup
  )

Now, for the origins that we have specific visitor count information for, we normalize specifically according to their home panels. One assumption needed here: for each original place we have raw_visit_counts and raw_visitor_counts. In order to attribute visits to visitors, we assume each visitor makes an average number of trips equal to raw_visit_counts/raw_visitor_counts.

But, we still have tons of unknown visitor origins. So were back to the same problem as with the macro approach of having to guess where theyre from in order to apply a home-based weight. First, Ill show just reverting to the macro approach for the unrecorded origins.

sj_weekly_200329_v2 <-
  sj_weekly_200329_expand %>% 
  mutate(
    origin_visit_counts =
      origin_visitor_counts*raw_visit_counts/raw_visitor_counts,
    visit_counts =
      ifelse(
        is.na(origin_census_block_group),
        origin_visit_counts*bay_multiplier,
        origin_visit_counts*pop/number_devices_residing
      )
  )
  
sj_weekly_200329_v2_sum <- 
  sj_weekly_200329_v2 %>% 
  pull(visit_counts) %>% 
  sum()

sj_weekly_200329_v2_sum
## [1] 6728841
sj_weekly_200329_v2_sum/sj_weekly_200329_v1_sum
## [1] 0.9978779

As expected, very similar because of how few recorded BGs there are.

By the way, heres the recorded origins block groups that had significant numbers of visitors for the SJ places.

sj_visitor_origins <-
  sj_weekly_200329_v2 %>% 
  filter(!is.na(origin_census_block_group)) %>% 
  group_by(origin_census_block_group) %>% 
  summarize(origin_visit_counts = sum(origin_visit_counts) %>% round())

sj_visitor_origins_map <-
  block_groups("CA",cb=F, progress_bar=F) %>% 
  right_join(sj_visitor_origins, by = c("GEOID"="origin_census_block_group")) %>% 
  dplyr::select(origin_visit_counts)

mapview(sj_visitor_origins_map)+mapview(sj_boundary, alpha.regions=0, lwd=1, color = "red")

V3: Micro method for recorded + Micro normalization for unrecorded

What if instead of using the whole Bay Area for normalization of the unrecorded origins, we assume that the unrecorded origins are more similar in sampling to the recorded BGs than to the Bay Area as a whole?

micro_pop <-
  ca_pop_blockgroup %>% 
  filter(
    origin_census_block_group %in% sj_weekly_200329_v2$origin_census_block_group
  ) %>% 
  pull(pop) %>% 
  sum()

micro_sg_pop <-
  ca_home_200329 %>% 
  filter(census_block_group %in% sj_weekly_200329_v2$origin_census_block_group) %>% 
  pull(number_devices_residing) %>% 
  sum()

micro_multiplier <- micro_pop/micro_sg_pop
sj_weekly_200329_v3 <-
  sj_weekly_200329_expand %>% 
  mutate(
    origin_visit_counts =
      origin_visitor_counts*raw_visit_counts/raw_visitor_counts,
    visit_counts =
      ifelse(
        is.na(origin_census_block_group),
        origin_visit_counts*micro_multiplier,
        origin_visit_counts*pop/number_devices_residing
      )
  )

sj_weekly_200329_v3_sum <- 
  sj_weekly_200329_v3 %>% 
  pull(visit_counts) %>% 
  sum()

sj_weekly_200329_v3_sum
## [1] 6595104
sj_weekly_200329_v3_sum/sj_weekly_200329_v1_sum
## [1] 0.9780449

Still only 2-3% different. I do suspect this method does produce meaningful effect with monthly patterns.

V4: Median method

We could use the distance_from_home for each individual place to find the block groups that are within that distance (radius method, or OSRM method). That would represent the possible origins of 50% of the visitors. Is it more accurate to normalize based on that group? Or do 50% of the normalization based on that group, and the other 50% reverts back to macro method? Maybe getting too complicated for just a few more % of change. I give up for now.
